A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly inadequate system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the ineffectiveness of this system, populist actors keep exploiting fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of relentless efforts.
That is why it is essential that this year a truly active approach be taken at both the European and global levels.
In September next, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to commit in a concrete and sustainable manner.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community could have limited the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon and Jordan – which together shelter no less than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed and provide education to refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to 21 billion euros each year in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are on a completely different scale from its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them asylum.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears by promoting an odious nationalist vision, either ignoring or distorting the lived experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found to have committed terrorist acts.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they receive in social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with political power in some European countries and are currently gaining support even within once-liberal strongholds.
Extremist anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote their own anti-immigration policies.
This situation has severely undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees arriving on its shores has only managed to "relocate" 190,000.
Border controls in six Schengen Area countries have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis is not only a matter for Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Regardless of everything, the EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence, which it will only be able to overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure pathways allowing refugees to reach Europe.
It is not a matter of asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
It remains nonetheless for the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to accept, and to employ orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would allow protecting migrants while safeguarding Europe (by enabling a full examination of applications).
Beyond a measure aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a strong global protection system for refugees and vulnerable migrants.
This objective will first require that more countries accept to host refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has only managed to relocate less than 75 percent of the approximately 20 million refugees annually.
Millions of them end up in a prolonged migration situation, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary that developed countries agree to host a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
The Canada having stated that it would host 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, it is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current situation, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the arrival of a large number of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
However, effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these groups remain seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving new arrivals of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the contrary, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit— including these countries (notably through inflows of money).
Last month, in Paris, the international community demonstrated that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better protection system for migrants.
It is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants—as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
